# FIMBY Notification Patterns

Cross-references: `fimby-design-philosophy.mdc` (voice), `fimby-architecture.mdc` (identity stamping, neighbourhood scoping, NOTIF_* constants), `fimby-apex-patterns.mdc` + `salesforce-apex-cursor-rules_apex-best-practices.mdc` (bulkification, repository pattern, no SOQL in loops).

---

## 1. Voice — neighbour, not platform

Notifications inherit the FIMBY voice from `fimby-design-philosophy.mdc`. Specifics for notification copy:

| Rule | Example |
|------|---------|
| Active voice, present tense | `Maya replied to your offer` not `A reply has been posted` |
| Lowercase first-person pronouns (`i`, `my`) | `i wanted to check in` not `I wanted to check in` |
| Recipient-aware second person (`you` / `your`) | `Maya wants to borrow your drill` not `A neighbour requested an item` |
| Non-punitive language | `Maya didn't respond yet` not `Maya failed to respond` |
| No exclamation marks | `Pickup is ready for Maple Co-op` not `Pickup is ready!` |
| No em dashes or en dashes | Use periods, commas, or new sentences. Em dashes are AI tells |
| No "Community Member", "User", "Member" labels | These read corporate. Use names; fall back to `'A neighbour'` |

## 2. Title shape

Three canonical patterns:

```
"{actor display name} {verb} {object phrase}"      // actor-initiated
"{thing} {state change}"                            // state-initiated, no actor
"Your {thing} {state change}"                       // state change targeting recipient
```

- `Title__c` **≤ 80 chars** (iOS lock-screen ceiling for push display)
- Never duplicate `actorName` inside the title text when `Actor_Name__c` is also set — the LWC renders both, doubling it reads broken

## 3. Body shape

- One sentence carrying the **deciding context** (date, quantity, location, deadline) so the recipient can decide whether to act without opening
- `Body__c` **≤ 140 chars**
- Empty string allowed when the title is fully self-contained; **never `null`**

## 4. Actor convention (mandatory)

`Actor_Name__c` is **always one of**:

1. **A human display name** resolved from the **represented identity** (`Posted_By__c` / `On_Behalf_Of__c` / acting-as Contact per the dual-stamp table in `fimby-architecture.mdc`).
   - Prefer **full name** by default
   - Use **first name only** when intimacy outweighs disambiguation — lending and bulk-buy domains
2. **A neighbourhood-team label**:
   - `'Neighbourhood team'` for moderator actions, vouch revoke/pause, support relationship lifecycle
   - `'FIMBY'` for system-initiated platform messages (auto-handoff, waitlist promotion, event reminders, bulk-buy broadcasts, system events)
3. **A documented icon token** *only* when it semantically replaces a person:

   | Token | Where used | LWC rendering |
   |-------|-----------|---------------|
   | `'care'` | Support relationship lifecycle | `fimbyNotificationsList` renders the support/care icon instead of initials |
   | `'system'` | Reserved for future platform-level messages | Same pattern as `'care'` — icon, not initials |

`null` and `''` are **banned outright**. The LWC initials avatar treats `''` as a missing name (renders blank) and `'care'` as initials `CA` (confusing) unless the token is documented above and the LWC opts into icon rendering by type.

## 5. URL convention (mandatory — enables the host swap)

**Strict separation by destination — both surfaces are CMDT-backed so admins can edit any URL via Setup → Custom Metadata Types without an Apex deploy.**

| Destination | Source CMDT | Apex helper | Rationale |
|-------------|-------------|-------------|-----------|
| Experience Cloud site (`our.fimby.com` today, `app.fimby.com` after universal-links) | `FIMBY_URL__mdt` (`Base_URL__c` + `Path__c`) | `FimbySettings.getUrl(devName, recordId?, querySuffix?)` | Single host-swap surface; **every record shares one `Base_URL__c` value** |
| Public website (`fimby.com/family-in-my-backyard/...` — explainers, terms, privacy, etc.) | `FIMBY_Public_Website_URL__mdt` (`Full_URL__c`) | `FimbyPublicWebsiteLinks.getUrl(devName)` | Outside Experience Cloud, **not affected by host swap** |

### Rules

- Every `Action_URL__c` on a notification → `FimbySettings.getUrl(...)`. **Never** hardcoded, **never** relative, **never** a public-website URL.
- Every Experience Cloud CTA in an email → `FimbySettings.getUrl(...)`. Same.
- Every public-website link in an email → `FimbyPublicWebsiteLinks.getUrl(...)`. **Never** via `FimbySettings.getUrl(...)`. **Never** a `FIMBY_URL__mdt` record.
- `FIMBY_URL__mdt` contract: every record's `Base_URL__c` is the same value. If you ever feel like adding a record with a different `Base_URL__c`, the URL belongs in `FIMBY_Public_Website_URL__mdt` instead.
- No hardcoded URL strings in Apex outside the two helper classes (`FimbySettings`, `FimbyPublicWebsiteLinks`).

### API

```apex
// Experience Cloud
FimbySettings.getUrl(developerName)                                  // page route, no record id
FimbySettings.getUrl(developerName, recordId)                        // record detail
FimbySettings.getUrl(developerName, recordId, querySuffix)           // record + query string (e.g. '?action=reviewRequest&requestId=...')

// Public website
FimbyPublicWebsiteLinks.getUrl(developerName)                        // returns Full_URL__c
```

### Email CTA double-prefix bug — historical context

`FimbyEmailHtmlBuilder.buildCtaUrl()` historically prepended `https://our.fimby.com` to `Action_URL__c` unconditionally. Once notifications started using `FimbySettings.getUrl()` (absolute URLs), email cards rendered `https://our.fimby.com/https://our.fimby.com/library-item/...`. The fix: if `Action_URL__c` is already absolute (`startsWithIgnoreCase('http')`), pass it through unchanged. New code should never depend on `buildCtaUrl()` performing host stitching.

## 6. Push payload deep-link metadata (server-only, dormant)

`FimbyPushNotificationService.PushPayload.data` carries two optional fields on every single-notification push:

- `action_url` — the same value stored in `Notification__c.Action_URL__c`
- `notification_id` — the `Notification__c.Id`

Batched pushes (one generic push per gate per user) include `action_url` **only when the batch covers exactly one underlying notification**.

**Mobile behavior is unchanged.** `resolvePushRoute()` in the mobile app currently routes to `/messages` (DM gate) or `/notifications` (activity gate) based on `channelId`. It does **not** read `action_url`. Per-target push routing is a separate product decision. The dormant payload exists so that decision becomes a 5-line mobile change later, not a coordinated SF + mobile release.

Push content (title / body) stays generic per the humane-push system: `"New message"`, `"Neighbourhood activity"`, panda messages. **Per-notification specifics live in the in-app inbox row and the email card, not in the push.**

## 7. Coverage rules — what produces a notification

These rules constrain which user actions produce a notification. They prevent gap-fill audits from growing rows we deliberately want silent.

- **Content edits do not notify.** Editing a story, post, library item, comment, profile field, etc. never produces a notification to anyone. The author owns the artifact; followers see the change next time they view.
- **Content deletes do not notify when nothing is pending.** Deleting a story with comments — no notification (no pending action). Deleting a closed/fulfilled post — no notification.
- **Content deletes DO notify when something is pending.** Deleting a library item with active borrow requests, archiving an asks/offers post with un-resolved responders, cancelling an event with RSVPs — these notify because the affected party expected to act.
- **Actions taken on behalf of the recipient always notify** (dual-stamp rule from `fimby-architecture.mdc` — the represented identity gets the notification, not just the real actor).
- **System-driven state changes notify** when the recipient lost an option (waitlist promotion, request lapsed, capacity reached).

## 8. Vouching is system messaging (no opt-out)

Vouching is trust infrastructure. All `Vouch_*` notification types are treated like account-safety messages — **no per-category toggle, no opt-out, bypass every standard gate** (master push toggle, per-category toggles, doorbell fatigue, quiet hours).

Affected types: `Vouch_Request_Received`, `Vouch_Request_Reminder`, `Vouch_Approved`, `Vouch_Declined`, `Vouch_Revoked`, `Voucher_Paused`.

Implementation:
- Push side: members of `FimbyNotificationService.SECURITY_BYPASS_PUSH_TYPES`
- Email side: members of `FimbyEmailAlertService.SECURITY_BYPASS_EMAIL_TYPES`
- Settings UI: covered by the static "Account & Safety" line, no toggle

## 9. Dual-check ownership (per `fimby-architecture.mdc`)

When deciding whether a viewer can see a notification or click through, accept access via **either**:

- `Notification__c.Contact__c == actingAsContactId` (the represented identity), **OR**
- The notification's related record's real-actor field matches `realContactId`

Single-field checks break for users acting as another identity. Use `FimbyIdentityRepository` to resolve both IDs.

## 10. Blocking

Notification list queries must filter by `FimbyBlockingHelper.getBidirectionalBlocks(viewerContactId)` against both the **represented identity** field and the **real actor** field on the related record. Do not re-implement bidirectional block queries inline.
